Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 61 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the South East Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 49 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
------------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 57 171 new cases (57.0% of the global newly reported cases), and 3356 deaths (77.3%) for this 24-hour period. Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 42.2% were reported by the USA, 28.9% were reported by Brazil, Peru 7.1 %, Chile 6.5 %, and Mexico 5.8%. The Americas region is maintaining its status as having the highest cumulative case count of the 6 WHO regions, with the European region as the 2nd-highest region.

The European region reported 18 192 new cases (18.1% of the global newly reported cases) and 543 deaths (12.5%). Russia reported 49.2% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, followed by the UK 13.2%, Turkey 6.3%, Belarus 5.2%, Italy 2.9%, and Spain 2.6% (?weekend artifact?)

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 12 026 new cases (12.0% of the global newly reported cases) and 176 deaths (4.1%). Saudi Arabia reported 19.9% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Pakistan 14.5%, Iran 18.1%, Qatar 12.5%, Kuwait 7.0%, the United Arab Emirates 6.5%, Egypt 6.3%, and Afghanistan and Oman at 4.3% each.

The African region reported 2707 new cases (2.7% of the global newly reported cases) and 47 deaths (1.1%). South Africa reported 45.8% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria at 11.6%, Algeria at 7.1%, Guinea and Sierra Leone at 3.7% each, South Sudan at 3.4%, and Ethiopia at 3.3%.

The Western Pacific region reported 927 new cases (0.92% of the global newly reported cases) and 16 deaths (0.37%). Singapore reported 59.1% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines 27.8%, Malaysia 6.5%, and Japan 3.3%. Singapore, the Philippines, and Malaysia account for 93.4% of the total newly reported cases in the region.

The South East Asia region reported 9241 new cases (9.2% of the global newly reported cases) and 204 deaths (4.7%). India reported 75.5% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh 16.6%, and Indonesia 5.7%. These 3 countries make up 97.8% of all reported cases in the region.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 25 May 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. Europe has significantly decreased. The Americas is increasing, as is South East Asia and the Eastern Mediterranean.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkins' CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the Johns Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
